[normal]Written evidence submitted by[bold] Bail for Immigration Detainees (JRR 0014)[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Bail for Immigration Detainees[bold]BID is an independent charity 
[normal]which
[normal] provides immigration detainees with
[normal] free legal advice, information and
[normal] representation
[normal] to secure their release from detention
[normal]. 
[normal]From 1 August 2012 to 31 July 2013, BID assisted 3367 people held in immigration detention.  
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Summary [bold]The Government’s proposals would place severe restrictions on immigration detainees’ access to judicial review, which is a crucial mechanism for safeguarding individual rights and preventing unlawful government conduct. 
[normal]Introduction [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Standing and third party interventions[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“Public law is not at base about rights, even though abuses of power may and often do invade private rights; it is about wrongs – that is to say misuses of public power; and the courts 
[normal]have always been alive to the fact that a person or organisation with no particular stake in the issue or the outcome may, without in any sense being a mere meddler, wish and be well placed to call the attention of the court to an apparent misuse of public
[normal] power. If an arguable case of such misuse can be made out on an application for [permission to bring judicial review], the court’s only concern is to ensure that it is not being done for an ill motive” (Sedley J in R v Somerset County Council, ex p Dixon 
[normal][1998] Env LR 111 at 117-121)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]"Judicial reviews are brought by groups who seek nothing more than cheap headlines"
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
