[normal]Where payment is discreti[bold]onary it probably won’t be made: evidence [bold]from the [bold]Exceptional Funding Scheme[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“In total the [Legal Aid Agency] had received 213 applications for non-inq
[normal]uest cases.  Of these, 146 were in family law and 63 in immigration.  There had been only two grants of funding: one in an immigration case concerning EU law and one in a family case.  In the [one] immigration case, funding was only granted after a pre-act
[normal]ion protocol letter was sent”
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Examples of cases which would be affected [bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Challenging delays in Home Office decision-making [bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Unlawful detention claims: family separation [bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Judicial reviews to challenge removal from the UK[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Case study[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Faith was detained with her partner for 206 days after serving a prison sentence. Her four children were aged between one and eleven when she went to prison; the eldest child was a British Citizen. The children were extremely distressed, and some of them d
[normal]eveloped behavioural and health problems.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Three months into her detention, the Home Office wrote to Faith and her partner informing them that they intended to remove the parents and children together. The family had been separated for two years and five
[normal] months. The Home Office noted the need for the children to “re-establish their relationship with their parents before remova
[normal]l,”
[normal] and envisaged that this might happen at Heathrow Airport. It is extremely concerning to see that the Home Office thought it wou
[normal]ld be appropriate to reunite these extremely distressed children with their parents during the course of their forced removal. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This removal attempt was cancelled, and the Home Office arranged a new date for the family to be removed using the same method,
[normal] but this was prevented by a judicial review application. The parents were subsequently released from detention and granted leave to remain in the UK. 
[normal]&#xa0;
