[normal]The Ministry of Justice has conceded that applications for release from detention on bail or temporary admission, and judicial reviews challenging the legality of detention would 
[normal]be
[normal] exempt from the residence test (Ministry of Justice September 2013 
[normal]Transforming Legal Aid: Next Steps, Annex B: Response to consultation, 
[normal]Paragraph 125). 
[normal]However, civil claims for compensation 
[normal]and damages 
[normal]for periods of unlawful detention, made after re
[normal]lease, would be subject to the residence test. If the decision under challenge – in this case to maintain detention – is withdrawn by the Home Office before the decision of the court is handed down, or an injunction ordering release is sought and granted, 
[normal]then any public law elements of the unlawful detention judicial review become academic and must be determined as part of a separate civil claim for damages.
